Fixed Acidity

As we can see in the figure the most wine have fixed acidity between 6 and 9 g/dm^3,also the The mean is 8.32 and the max is 15.90.

Volatile acidity

As we can see in the figure the peak at 0.4,the most wine have fixed acidity between 0.3 and 0.7 g/dm^3 and the mean is 0.52 and the max is 1.58.

Citric acid

Most red wine contains quantity small citric acid. The Citric acid exists in greater than in a fruits,the most notably citrus fruits like Lemons. The Most red wine have 0 g/dm^3.

Residual sugar

As we can see in the above figure the distribution represent the right skewed. The mean is 2.539 g/dm^3 and the max is 15.500 g/dm^3.

Chlorides

As we can see The distribution in chloride is symmetric and we can see the peak at 0.09 g/dm^3 The mean is 0.08747 g/dm^3.

Free sulfur dioxide

As we can see The distribution in free sulfur dioxide s right skewed and we can see the peak at 5 g/dm^3 The mean is 15.87 g/dm^3.

Total sulfur dioxide

As we can see The distribution in total sulfur dioxide is right skewed and we can see the peak betwwen 23 and 24 g/dm^3,The mean is 6.00 g/dm^3 and the max 289.

Density

As we can see The distribution in density is symmetric, and we can see the most red wine have density between 0.9950 - 0.9980 The mean is 0.9967 g/cm^3.

pH

As we can see in the above figure the distribution represent symmetric. The mean is 3.311 and the max is 4.010.

Sulphates

As we can see The distribution in sulphates is right skewed and we can see the peak betwwen 3.3 and 3.4 ,The mean is 0.6581 g/dm^3 and the max 2 g/dm^3, and there are outliers.

Alcohol

As we can see The distribution in alcohol is right skewed and we can see the peak betwwen 9.1 and 9,5 ,The mean is 10.42 and the max 14.90 .

Bivariate Plots Section

As a starting point let us have a look at a correlation matrix:

As we can see in the correlation matrix there is positive correlation between density and fixed.acidity , and negative correlation between total.sulfur.dioxide and alcohol ,positive correlation between density and residual.sugar.

As we can see in the figure above whenever you higher the alcohol is the higher the quality the correlation between alcohol and quality called positive relationship.

As we can see in the figure above whenever you lower the volatile.acidity is the higher the qualith the correlation between volatile.acidity and qualith called inverse relationship.

As we can see in the figure above whenever you higher the sulphates is the higher the quality the correlation coefficient between sulphates and quality called positive relationship.

Reflection

In the beginng we chose the Red Wine Quality dataset it’s has 1599 kind of wines and 12 variants,then we started understand the variables by do explored every variable.

After that we have some question and tryied to solved by do correlation matricx and did visualize the relationships between the variables and see if there any relationship.

We noticed that there is strong positive relastionship between alcohol and quality so, we can say to get red Wine with high Quality you suppposed we have high alcohol . and there some varibles as voilatile.acidity has reverse relationship.

As we can predict the quality of wine by using alcohol and voilatile.acidity in case we look for high quality we will see alcohol and in case we look for low quality we will see voilatile.acidity

It is also possible that if we had a dataset and variables bigger then our dataset on red wine, the analysis would be more accurate to confirm that alcohol increases the quality of red wine.
